data.content:
MSTest has dedicated collection and null assertions that give **much better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // no built-in "assert all" — IsTrue is fine here
    var admin = users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Before | After | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | Removed (redundant — `AreEqual(3, …)` covers it) | Less noise |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | Failure shows *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of *"Expected: True, Actual: False"* |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Clearer intent and message |

**General rule:** if a specialized assert exists (`AreEqual`, `IsNotNull`, `IsInstanceOfType`, `ThrowsException`), prefer it over `IsTrue` — you get actionable failure messages for free.
